Date: Thu, 17 Mar 2016 14:11:11 +0800
Subject: [PATCH 7/8] grsec: add prevention mechanisms to the kernel that
 reduce the risks

The origin patch is from
deb.digdeo.fr/grsecurity-archives/kernel-4.1/grsecurity-3.1-4.1.7-201509201149.patch

PAX_NOEXEC Do not allow for protecting memory pages against execution or
even if they do, Linux does not make use of this feature.  In practice
this means that if a page is readable (such as the stack or heap) it is
also executable.

PAX_PAGEEXEC/ PAX_SEGMEXEC are based on the paging/segmentation feature of
the CPU and has a very small performance impact.

PAX_EMUTRAMP prevents some programs and libraries that for one reason or
another attempt to execute special small code snippets from non-executable
memory pages.  Most notable examples are the signal handler return code
generated by the kernel itself and the GCC trampolines

PAX_EMUSIGRT enalbe kernel automatically detect and emulate signal return
trampolines executing on the stack.

